{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600420"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:02:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:02:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15611"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15611"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8302"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7009"},{"type":"tags","id":"10131"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20043"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHyperparathyroidism is classified as primary, secondary, or tertiary based on the underlying pathophysiology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes tertiary hyperparathyroidism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autonomous parathyroid function after chronic kidney disease","Direct stimulation of parathyroid glands by hypocalcaemia","Solitary parathyroid adenoma secreting excess hormone","Compensatory increase in parathyroid hormone from vitamin D deficiency","Multiple endocrine neoplasia causing parathyroid hyperplasia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn tertiary hyperparathyroidism, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eautonomous parathyroid function\u003C/strong\u003E develops as a consequence of prolonged secondary hyperparathyroidism, particularly in patients with chronic kidney disease. Even when the original trigger is addressed, the glands continue to produce excessive amounts of parathyroid hormone independently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo understand why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of parathyroid glands\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of secondary hyperparathyroidism where the glands respond appropriately to low calcium levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolitary parathyroid adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E typically cause primary hyperparathyroidism through spontaneous tumour development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompensatory increase in parathyroid hormone\u003C/strong\u003E describes secondary hyperparathyroidism where the response is appropriate to vitamin D deficiency\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple endocrine neoplasia\u003C/strong\u003E represents an inherited condition causing primary hyperparathyroidism through genetic mechanisms\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Parathyroid glands can become independently overactive following prolonged periods of compensatory hyperactivity","When calcium levels are chronically low, parathyroid glands increase their hormone production as a natural response","Patients with long-term kidney failure commonly develop autonomous parathyroid overactivity"],"references":["Casella C, Guarneri C, Campanile M, Adhoute X, Gelera PP, Morandi R. Surgical treatment of tertiary hyperparathyroidism: does one fit for all? Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2023 Nov 2;14:1226917. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2023.1226917. PMID: 38027172; PMCID: PMC10652876.","Madkhali T, Alhefdhi A, Chen H, Elfenbein D. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Ulus Cerrahi Derg. 2016 Mar 1;32(1):58-66. doi: 10.5152/UCD.2015.3032. PMID: 26985167; PMCID: PMC4771429.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15611"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55939"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T14:35:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T14:37:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8302"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70475"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}